description:
I spent a few days near the Arch Street Friends Meeting House in downtown Philadelphia. It's deep in the urban matrix but surrounded by a lovely courtyard full of thankfully-unpesticided grass and some grand old trees, including white oak and tulip poplars and sweetgum.

On my first morning a flash of vibrant pink in the canopy led to a rose-breasted grosbeak ... and then a whole host of migratory birds. So I made a game of trying to photograph every species I could find there.

description:
Sat perched even when I was 5 feet away. 

I barely saw this bird as it perched on a fallen tree. It sat still and blended in with the tree's coloring and texture. As I got very close, it finally flew to a bush a few feet away. All the while, it remained close to ground level. In comparison, the bird was slightly smaller than a house sparrow, and the way it remained close-by and watched me was similar to catbird behavior.

Observed this woodpecker climbing up and down a tree feeding on insects. 

This bird was about 16 inches in length and zig-zagged up the tree as it fed. It swooped off and vocalized a clear, loud call. This was a brief series of high pitched sounds. Personally, it sounded like laughter. It reappeared on a large tree directly across the creek and continued feeding by circling up the trunk.

This area is about 15 minutes away from where I had a casual observation on May 24, 2020.

Record the drumming, while it's insight.

description: The double crested cormorant is a common and sleek seabird found throughout North America. Their populations have fluctuated in recent history - taking a hit due to the boom in use of pesticides in the 1900s. Since then, their populations have bounced back and have been steadily increasing - likely due to the warming climate. While their populations are at a healthy number now, increasing expansion of their range due to climate change can pose risks for other seabirds that haven’t been faring as well. Soon, the double created cormorant could be too dominant.
